Package au.edu.anu.twcore.ecosystem.runtime.system

Class CategorizedContainer<T extends fr.cnrs.iees.identity.Identity>

java.lang.Object
au.edu.anu.twcore.ecosystem.runtime.system.CategorizedContainer<T>
All Implemented Interfaces:
Container, DynamicContainer<T>, NestedContainer<T>, NestedDynamicContainer<T>, ResettableContainer<T>, SimpleContainer<T>, fr.cnrs.iees.identity.Identity, fr.ens.biologie.generic.Resettable, fr.ens.biologie.generic.Sealable
Direct Known Subclasses:
DescribedContainer
public abstract class CategorizedContainer<T extends fr.cnrs.iees.identity.Identity> extends Object implements NestedContainer<T>, NestedDynamicContainer<T>, ResettableContainer<T>, SimpleContainer<T>, fr.ens.biologie.generic.Resettable, fr.ens.biologie.generic.Sealable

The class holding the SystemComponents (actually, any object with an id (class Identity) can be stored in such containers) at runtime, and responsible for their creation and deletion.

The rule is: all items (type T) contained in this class have the same data structure. The data structure is defined by the categoryInfo field, which refers to a set of categories which tell how data is associated to this container. These data consist in constant values (parameters) and values varying with time (variables). Both are available as ReadOnlyPropertyList in this class, since it's not its business to know how to change the values.

A container can have sub-containers, so that they can be organized in a hierarchy.

This class is meant to be used at runtime in a time-synchronized way: changes (additions and deletions) are only recorded, but not effected until the effectChanges() or effectAllChanges() method is called.

This class is meant to hold a population of simulated items, starting with an initial population that can be reset later, i.e. the whole container can revert to an initial state.

Author:
Jacques Gignoux - 1 juil. 2019

    • itemListPointerUseWithCaution

      public final Collection<T> itemListPointerUseWithCaution()
      CAUTION: this method exposes the item list without protection (as items() does). This is for objects that need to manipulate the list of items without changing it, but require that the list can change by itself between calls. In other words, for objects that just keep a pointer to the list in read-only mode. Unfortunately there is no such thing as a read-only collecion in java.
      Returns:
      the address of the item list.
